article.description: Bobby Jackson led a potent  bench with 18 points and starter Peja Stojakovic scored 20 as the Sacramento Kings continued their domination of the Golden State Warriors with a 117-91 victory.
article.headline: Kings cruise to 14th straight win over Warriors
article.linkText: Seven Kings hit double figures in 14th straight win over Warriors
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Even at "73.5 percent effectiveness,'' Scot Pollard was too tough for the Golden State Warriors.
Pollard

Pollard had 15 points and 12 rebounds, and Peja Stojakovic scored 20 points to lead seven Kings in double figures as Sacramento beat the Warriors for the 14th straight time, 117-91 Tuesday night. While the rest of the team tuned up for Thursday's showdown with the Los Angeles Lakers by pounding their favorite punching bags, Pollard used his 26 minutes of playing time to get in shape -- and to remind the Kings just how much they've missed him. Playing in just his 10th game during an injury-plagued season, Pollard provided the hustle, interior defense and key rebounds that made him one of Sacramento's unsung heroes in past seasons. When Sacramento put away the undermanned Warriors with a 31-6 run in the second half, Pollard was at the center of the rally. "I haven't got time to get back in shape. I need to be out there now,'' said Pollard, whose shaved head and trucker's mustache haven't caught on in Sacramento the way his previous tonsorial choices did. "I'm at about 73, maybe 73.5 percent effectiveness right now. The main thing I can give is effort and solid minutes. I'm just looking to run, get in shape and get some rebounds. That's what I care about,'' Pollard said. Pollard got to do plenty of running against the Warriors, whose uptempo offense reminds many of the Kings during the 1999 season, when they began building the experience that has made them one of the NBA's elite. Chris Webber had 13 points and 10 rebounds, and Jim Jackson scored 14 points for Sacramento, which has won 18 of its last 19 home meetings with Golden State. Bobby Jackson scored 18 points for the Kings, who took control with a lengthy run spanning the third and fourth quarters. Pollard contributed several baskets and rebounds during the stretch. "Maybe people forgot what Scot brings us,'' Sacramento coach Rick Adelman said. "He reminded them tonight. Scot gives us something we don't have. He's tough, he sets screens, he gets rebounds. We needed all of them tonight.'' Gilbert Arenas had 22 points for Golden State, and rookie Mike Dunleavy had 15 points and seven rebounds in his first NBA start. The Warriors lost for the fifth time in seven games, though they gave a test to the Pacific Division-leading Kings before wilting in the second half with just nine players in uniform. Jason Richardson scored all 14 of his points in the first half. Antawn Jamison had 18 points and seven rebounds for the Warriors. Troy Murphy missed the game with a bruised right knee, forcing Golden State to change its starting lineup for the first time all season. Murphy, Jamison, Richardson, Arenas and Erick Dampier had started all 66 games. "We ran out of gas with limited bodies,'' Golden State coach Eric Musselman said. "I think our shooting percentage (36 percent) was indicative of us not having legs. I thought we played three great quarters. We just lost our legs.'' The Kings' reserves outscored Golden State's 66-10, and Sacramento outrebounded the Warriors 66-48 while improving to an NBA-best 29-6 at home. Two days after a dispiriting overtime home loss to league-leading Dallas, the Kings weathered Golden State's strong early play and responded with an outstanding second half, scoring at will on offense and shutting down the Warriors on defense. "We came out with a lot of confidence in the beginning,'' Arenas said. "We weren't going to let them bully us like they usually do the last 14 times we've come here. (But) their whole team contributed tonight, and it just fell apart.'' Dunleavy responded to his bigger role with some of the most aggressive play of his rookie year. He scored 12 points in the first half on 5-of-7 shooting.

Game notes
The Kings' offense wasn't all bright. Doug Christie went 0-for-7 and finished scoreless, while Mike Bibby scored just six points. ... Dallas and Golden State are the only teams averaging more points per game than Sacramento. ... The Warriors' streak was the longest streak by any Golden State starting five since the team moved West in 1962. ... Danny Fortson, the Warriors' starting power forward last season, missed another game for what the team called "personal reasons'' _ though Fortson attended the game in street clothes. Fortson has fallen out of Musselman's rotation and hasn't taken the demotion well.
